1 regulation, and taxation of captive insurance companies by entities in the State; and
2 generally relating to the State insurance premium receipts tax captive insurers.
3 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
4 Article – Insurance
5 Section 4–209 and 4–211
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2017 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Insurance
11 4–209.
12 (a) This section does not apply to:
13 (1) premiums on lawfully procured surplus lines insurance;
14 (2) premiums on independently procured insurance on which a tax has
15 been paid under § 4–211 of this subtitle; [or]
16 (3) PREMIUMS ON LAWFULLY PROCURED CAPTIVE INSURANCE BY:
17 (I) A NONPROFIT HEALTH CARE SYSTEM LOCATED IN THE
18 STATE, INCLUDING PREMIUMS PAID BY THE SYSTEM’S PARENT ENTITY, ANY
19 SUBSIDIARY ENTITY, OR ANY CONSTITUENT HEALTH CARE PROVIDER; OR
20 (II) A NONPROFIT HOSPITAL LOCATED IN THE STATE; OR
21 (4) wet marine and transportation insurance.
22 (b) (1) If an unauthorized insurer effects, continues, or renews insurance on a
23 subject resident, located, or to be performed in the State, the unauthorized insurer shall
24 pay to the Commissioner, before March 1 of the next calendar year, a premium receipts tax
25 of 3% of gross premiums charged for the insurance.
26 (2) For policies effective before July 21, 2011:
27 (i) if the policy covers property, risks, or exposures located or to be
28 performed entirely in the State, the premium receipts tax shall be computed on the entire
29 premium at the rate specified in paragraph (1) of this subsection; and
30 (ii) if the policy covers property, risks, or exposures located or to be
31 performed both in and outside the State, the premium receipts tax shall be computed at the

SENATE BILL 890 3
1 rate specified in paragraph (1) of this subsection only on that portion of the premium that
2 is properly allocable to the risks located in the State.
3 (3) For policies effective on or after July 21, 2011, if the State is the
4 insured’s home state, the premium receipts tax shall be computed on the entire premium
5 at the rate specified in paragraph (1) of this subsection.
6 (4) Insurance that an unauthorized insurer effects, continues, or renews on
7 a subject resident, located, or to be performed in the State that is procured through
8 negotiations or an application wholly or partly occurring or made in or from within or
9 outside of the State, or for which premiums wholly or partly are remitted directly or
10 indirectly from in or outside of the State, is deemed to be insurance procured, continued, or
11 renewed in the State.
12 (c) The premium receipts tax under this section is instead of all other State taxes.
13 (d) If an unauthorized insurer defaults on the payment of the tax under this
14 section, the insured shall pay the tax.
15 (e) If the tax is not timely paid under subsection (b) of this section, the amount of
16 the tax due shall be increased by a penalty of:
17 (1) 25% of the tax due; and
18 (2) an amount computed at the rate of 1% per month or any part of a month
19 after the date the payment was due to the date the payment is made.
20 4–211.
21 (a) This section does not apply to:
22 (1) PREMIUMS ON LAWFULLY PROCURED CAPTIVE INSURANCE BY:
23 (I) A NONPROFIT HEALTH CARE SYSTEM LOCATED IN THE
24 STATE, INCLUDING PREMIUMS PAID BY THE SYSTEM’S PARENT ENTITY, ANY
25 SUBSIDIARY ENTITY, OR ANY CONSTITUENT HEALTH CARE PROVIDER; OR
26 (II) A NONPROFIT HOSPITAL LOCATED IN THE STATE; OR
27 (2) wet marine and transportation insurance.
28 (b) (1) If an insured procures, continues, or renews insurance from an
29 unauthorized insurer that is subject to a report under § 4–210 of this subtitle, a premium
30 receipts tax of 3% of the gross premiums charged for the insurance is levied on the
31 obligation, chose in action, or right represented by the premium charged for the insurance.

4 SENATE BILL 890
1 (2) If an insurance contract subject to the tax is canceled and rewritten, the
2 additional premium, for purposes of the premium receipts tax, is the premium in excess of
3 the unearned premium of the canceled insurance contract.
4 (c) If the insured fails to withhold from the premium the amount of the tax levied
5 under this section, the insured is liable for the amount of the tax imposed under subsection
6 (b) of this section and shall pay the tax to the Commissioner.
7 (d) If the tax imposed under subsection (b) of this section is not timely paid, the
8 amount of the tax due shall be increased by a penalty of:
9 (1) 25% of the tax due; and
10 (2) an amount computed at the rate of 1% per month or part of a month
11 after the date the payment is due until the date the payment is made.
12 (e) If the tax is not timely paid under this section, on request of the Commissioner,
13 the Attorney General shall proceed in a court of this State or another state or in a federal
14 court or agency to recover the tax:
15 (a) The Maryland Insurance Administration, in consultation with relevant
16 stakeholders, shall study the use, regulation, and taxation of captive insurance companies
17 by entities in the State.
18 (b) The study conducted under subsection (a) of this section shall examine:
19 (1) utilization of captive insurance by nonprofit and for–profit entities;
20 (2) existing federal and state regulatory and taxation frameworks that
21 apply to captive insurance, including states with and without established captive insurance
22 frameworks, focusing on:
23 (i) mechanisms used for funding regulatory oversight; and
24 (ii) how other states tax capital contributions and internal reserves,
25 including whether different tax treatments are applied based on the nonprofit or for–profit
26 status of the captive owner;
27 (3) the feasibility, utility, and potential structure of establishing a State
28 registry for captive insurance companies domiciled in other jurisdictions but used by
29 entities in the State, including an analysis of how a registry framework could provide
30 regulatory transparency and fund oversight operations as an alternative to a premium tax
31 framework; and
32 (4) the aggregate results of any completed investigations regarding the use
33 of captive insurance by nonprofit and for–profit entities in the State.

SENATE BILL 890 5
1 (c) Any data, documents, or other information provided by a nonprofit health
2 system or hospital to the Administration for the purpose of the evaluation and assessment
3 required under this section:
4 (1) shall be considered confidential commercial and financial information;
5 (2) may not be disclosed by the Administration to any third party; and
6 (3) is not a public record and is not subject to inspection under the Public
7 Information Act.
8 (d) On or before December January 1, 2027, the Administration shall report its
9 findings and recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the
10 State Government Article, the Senate Finance Committee and the House Health
11 Committee.
12 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the:
13 (a) The Maryland Insurance Administration may not charge or collect the
14 premium receipts tax under § 4–209 or § 4–211 of the Insurance Article otherwise payable
15 before the effective date of this Act or a fee, penalty, or interest accrued for failure to pay
16 that tax before the effective date of this Act from an unauthorized insurer exempt from the
17 tax under § 4–209(a)(3) of the Insurance Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, or an
18 insured exempt from the tax under § 4–211(a)(1) of the Insurance Article, as enacted by
19 Section 1 of this Act from captive insurance lawfully procured by a nonprofit entity.
20 (b) The prohibition established under subsection (a) of this section shall apply to
21 any existing and retroactive tax liabilities under § 4–209 or § 4–211 of the Insurance
22 Article.
23 SECTION 3. 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
24 July 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 2 years and, at the
25 end of June 30, 2028, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the General
26 Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
